 recording sales certifications|sales thresholds]])</small>\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|- style=\"width:4em;font-size:85%;\"\n! style=\"width:30px;\"|[[Billboard Hot 100|US]]\n! style=\"width:30px;\"|[[Dance Club Songs|US Dance]]<ref name=\"BB - Singles (Dance)\">{{cite web |title=Ultra Nat\u00e9 Album & Song Chart History|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=ultra nat\u00e9|chart=Dance/Club Play Songs}}|work=[[Billboard.com]]|accessdate=January 8, 2012}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:30px;\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br/><ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book | first= David | last= Roberts | year= 2006 | title= British Hit Singles & Albums | edition= 19th | publisher= Guinness World Records Limited | location= London | isbn= 1-904994-10-5 | page= 388}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:30px;\"|[[Canadian Singles Chart|CAN]]\n|-\n| 1989\n|align=\"left\"|\"It's Over Now\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| 62\n| \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''[[Blue Notes in the Basement]]''\n|-\n| 1991\n|align=\"left\"|\"Is It Love?\"\n| \u2014\n| 45\n| 71\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n|align=\"left\"|\"Rejoicing (I'll Never Forget)\"\n| \u2014\n| 7\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n|align=\"left\"|\"Joy\"\n| \u2014\n| 2\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''[[One Woman's Insanity]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1994\n|align=\"left\"|\"Show Me\"\n| \u2014\n| 1\n| 62\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"How Long\"\n| \u2014\n| 2\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Free (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Free]]\"\n| 75\n| 1\n| 4\n| 10\n|\n*UK: Gold\n| rowspan=\"5\"|''[[Situation: Critical]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|1998\n|align=\"left\"|\"Free (Remix)<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Charts Company, Artist Chart History, Ultra Nate|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/ultra%20nate/|website=Officialcharts.com|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref>\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| 33\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Found a Cure (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Found a Cure]]\"\n| \u2014\n| 1\n| 6\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[New Kind of Medicine]]\"\n| \u2014\n| 28\n| 14\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"Pressure\"\n| \u2014\n| 3\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[If You Could Read My Mind]]\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Stars on 54: Ultra Nat\u00e9, [[Amber (singer)|Amber]], [[Jocelyn Enriquez]])</span>\n| 52\n| 3\n| 23\n| 7\n|\n| ''[[54 (film)|54]] soundtrack''\n|-\n| 2000\n|align=\"left\"|\"Desire\"\n| \u2014\n| 1\n| 40\n| \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"4\"|''[[Stranger Than Fiction (Ultra Nate album)|Stranger Than Fiction]]''\n|-\n| 2001\n|align=\"left\"|\"Get It Up (The Feeling)\"\n| \u2014\n| 1\n| 51\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2002\n|align=\"left\"|\"I Don't Understand It\"\n| \u2014\n| 25\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"Twisted\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Brass in Pocket]]\"\n| \u2014\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n| Non-album single\n|-\n|2004\n|align=\"left\"|\"Free\" (Remixes)\n<small>(Oscar G, Brick City, Corbett & Troia remix)</small>\n|align=\"left\"|\n|23\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\n|Free (Remixes)\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2005\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Freak On]]\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Ultra Nat\u00e9 vs [[StoneBridge (DJ)|Stonebridge]])</span>\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| 37\n| \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"4\"|''[[Grime, Silk, & Thunder]]''\n|-\n| 2006\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Love's the Only Drug]]\"\n| \u2014\n| 2\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2007\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Automatic (Pointer Sisters song)#Ultra Nat\u00e9 cover|Automatic]]\"\n| \u2014\n| 1\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Give It All You Got (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Give It All You Got]]\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with [[Chris Willis]])</span>\n| \u2014\n| 1\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|align=\"left\"|\"Twisted (Got Me Goin' Round)\"\n| \u2014\n| 3\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n| ''GST: Grime Silk & Thunder Reloaded''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2009\n|align=\"left\"|\"Faster Faster Pussycat (Let\u2019s Go!)\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''Things Happen at Night''\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"Hey DJ\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2011\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Turn It Up (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Turn It Up]]\"\n| \u2014\n| 4\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"5\"|''Hero Worship''\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"My Love\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Waiting on You (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Waiting on You]]\"<br><small>(with [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]])</small>\n| \u2014\n| 11\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n|align=\"left\"|\"Everybody Loves the Night\"\n| \u2014\n| 29\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2014\n|align=\"left\"|\"Unconditional\"\n| \u2014\n| 2\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n\n|align=\"left\"|\"So Glamorous\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with Samuele Sartini)</span>\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Non-album singles\n|-\n| 2015\n|align=\"left\"|\"Take Care of My Heart\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with Eddie Amador)</span>\n| \u2014\n| 21\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n\n|2016\n|align=\"left\"|Alive\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|align=\"left\"|I'm Too Sexy (Touch This Skin)\n| \u2014\n|7\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|''Black Stereo Faith''\n|-\n|2017\n|align=\"left\"|\"Fake\"<br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(S-Man & Ultra Nat\u00e9)</span>\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|Non-album single\n|}\n\n====As featured artist====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:300px;\"| Single\n! colspan=\"2\"|Peak chart positions\n|- style=\"width:4em;font-size:85%;\"\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:30px;\"|[[Dance Club Songs|US Dance]]\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:30px;\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br/><ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1992\n|align=\"left\"|\"Altitude\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(777 featuring Ultra Nat\u00e9)</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|44\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|1995\n|align=\"left\"|\"Party Girl (Turn Me Loose)\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"10.000 Screaming Faggots\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(The Moonwalkers feat. Ultra Nat\u00e9)</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1997\n|align=\"left\"|\"Partay Feeling\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[Erick Morillo|B-Crew]] featuring [[Barbara Tucker]], [[Dajae]], Ultra Nat\u00e9 and [[Mon\u00e9]])</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|45\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2004\n|align=\"left\"|\"Time of our Lives\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Ultra Devoted)</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|2005\n|align=\"left\"|\"Bittersweet Melody\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[Alex Gaudino|Gaudino]] feat. Ultra Nat\u00e9)</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"Wonderful Place\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[U.D.A.U.F.L.]])</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|2010\n|align=\"left\"|\"No Wasted Hearts\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(Nicola Fasano feat. Ultra Nat\u00e9)</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|\"Destination\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[Tony Moran]] feat. Ultra Nat\u00e9)</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|-\n|2018\n|\"Feeling Mighty\" <br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(David Harness, Ultra Nat\u00e9)</span>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of number-one dance hits (United States)]]\n*[[List of artists who reached number one on the US Dance chart]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ultranate.com Ultra Nat\u00e9] \u2014 official website\n\n{{Ultra Nat\u00e9}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nate, Ultra}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Havre de Grace, Maryland]]\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:American garage house musicians]]\n[[Category:American house musicians]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Tommy Boy Records artists]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Singers from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Deep house musicians]]\n[[Category:American women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2008}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Ultra Nat\u00e9\n| image            = Ultranate.JPG\n| caption          = Ultra Nat\u00e9 in 2007\n| image_size       = 220px\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Ultra Nat\u00e9\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1968|03|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[Havre de Grace, Maryland]], United States\n| genre            = {{flat list|\n*[[Dance music|Dance]]\n*[[garage house]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flat list|\n*[[Deee-lite]]\n*[[Crystal Waters]]\n*[[Basement Boys]]\n*Quentin Harris\n*[[Alex Gaudino]]\n*[[StoneBridge (DJ)|Stonebridge]]\n*[[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]]\n*Chris Willis\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flat list|\n*[[Singing|Singer]]\n*[[songwriter]]\n*[[record producer]]\n*[[Promoter (entertainment)|promoter]]\n*[[DJ]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 1989&ndash;present\n| label            = {{flat list|\n*[[Warner Bros. Records]]\n*[[Strictly Rhythm Records]]\n*[[Tommy Boy Entertainment|Silver Label/Tommy Boy Entertainment]]\n*[[Blufire/Peacebisquit]]\n}}\n| website          = http://www.ultranate.com/\n}}\n\n'''Ultra Nat\u00e9''' (born March 20, 1968) is an American singer, songwriter, record producer, DJ and promoter who has achieved success on the pop charts with songs such as \"[[Free (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Free]]\", \"[[If You Could Read My Mind]]\" (as part of [[Stars on 54]]), and [[Automatic (Pointer Sisters song)|\"Automatic\"]].\n\nVirtually all of her singles have reached the Top 10 of the US [[Hot Dance Club Play]] chart. Such singles include \"Show Me\", \"Free\", \"Desire\", \"Get it Up (the Feeling)\", \"[[Love's the Only Drug]]\", and her number-one hits \"[[Automatic (Pointer Sisters song)#Ultra Nat\u00e9 cover|Automatic]]\", \"[[Give It All You Got (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Give it All You Got]]\" featuring Chris Willis, \"Waiting On You\" and \"Everybody Loves the Night\". In December 2016, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard magazine]]'' ranked her as the 12th most successful dance artist of all-time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-top-dance-club-artists|title=Greatest of All Time Top Dance Club Artists : Page 1|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nBorn '''Ultra Nat\u00e9''' in [[Havre de Grace, Maryland]], United States, she displayed her singing talent at an early age. Growing up, Nat\u00e9 enjoyed a wide variety of music; she enjoyed listening to artists such as [[Marvin Gaye]] and [[Boy George]], whom Nat\u00e9 would later say helped her become more open to being more experimental with her style and production of music.<ref>{{cite news| author=DJ Ron Slomowicz| url=http://dancemusic.about.com/cs/interviews/a/IntUltraNateR.htm| title=Interview with Ultra Nate| publisher=Dance Music / Electronica| year=2007| accessdate=2007-09-21| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040803141550/http://dancemusic.about.com/cs/interviews/a/IntUltraNateR.htm| archivedate=2004-08-03}}</ref>\n\nShe is best known in her home country for her 1990s dance crossover track, \"Free\". She is also remembered in America for her team-up with [[Amber (singer)|Amber]] and [[Jocelyn Enriquez]] as [[Stars on 54]] on a 1998 cover of [[Gordon Lightfoot]]'s \"If You Could Read My Mind\", which was a minor mainstream American hit. It reached #52 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart and #3 on the [[Billboard Hot Dance Music/Club Play]] chart. Though she has had club success in America, she has found the majority of her singles and, especially, album sales success in [[Europe]].\n\n===Career===\nUltra Nat\u00e9 began her recording career on a major label, [[Warner Bros. Records]], signed through its British offices.<ref name=\"Larkin90\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Virgin Encyclopedia of Nineties Music]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=First|isbn=0-7535-0427-8|page=407}}</ref> Through it, she released her first two albums. Her debut album, ''[[Blue Notes in the Basement]]'' (1991) was created along with the [[Basement Boys]] and it featured the singles \"It's Over Now\", \"Deeper Love (Missing You)\", \"Is It Love\", and the gospel-tinged \"Rejoicing\".<ref name=\"Larkin90\"/>\n\nIn 1993, the [[alternative dance]]/[[house music|house]] ''[[One Woman's Insanity]]'' was released.<ref name=\"Larkin90\"/> Although it still featured the Basement Boys' production on several tracks, this time Ultra found herself working with [[Nellee Hooper]], and [[Kwame Kwaten#Biography|D-Influence]].<ref name=\"Larkin90\"/> At a time when soulful [[house music]] performers such as [[Robin S]] and [[Crystal Waters]] were scoring cross-over Top Ten Pop singles, it was believed that Ultra Nat\u00e9 would score a similar level of commercial success. Mainstream sales however were not achieved even though \"Show Me\" received moderate mainstream pop radio airplay. Singles included \"How Long\", \"Show Me\" (her first song to reach the top position on the US Dance charts) and \"Joy\". However, neither release sold very well, and she was dropped from the label.\n\nIn 1995, Ultra Nat\u00e9 contributed the song \"Party Girl (Turn Me Loose)\" to the soundtrack to the independent film starring [[Parker Posey]]. The single was commercially released by the [[King Street Sounds]] label.\n\nWhen Warner Bros. tried to push her in another direction, Ultra Nat\u00e9 left the major label and moved to the independent dance label, [[Strictly Rhythm]]. It was here that \"Free\", her biggest mainstream hit, was released in 1997.<ref name=\"Larkin90\"/> The song, co-written by Nat\u00e9, Lem Springsteen and John Ciafone while production was held by both Springsteen and Ciafone, enjoyed heavy airplay throughout the summer, not only in clubs, but on rhythmic and mainstream radio stations in America and Europe. \"Free\" peaked at number 75 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100. It became a substantial hit in the UK, where it peaked at number four in the [[UK Singles Chart]], helping its parent album 'Situation: Critical' reach number seventeen on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref name=\"Larkin90\"/> It was also successful in Canada where it reached number 10 at the Canadian Singles Charts.<ref>{{cite news | author=| url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r351038/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}} | title= AllMusicGuide entry | website=[[AllMusic]]| date=2007-07-27 | accessdate=2007-07-27}}</ref>\n\nIt was with this album that Ultra Nat\u00e9's greatest commercial success was achieved, particularly in Europe, where singles such as \"Found a Cure\" (No. 6 in the UK), and \"New Kind of Medicine\" (No 14 UK) also charted.\n\nIn 1998, a new single \"Pressure\" was released internationally. Taken from the soundtrack to the film ''The 24 Hour Woman'', it contained three club mixes. The original version of the track was found on 'Situation: Critical\" but listed as \"Release the Pressure\".\n\nHer follow-up album ''[[Stranger Than Fiction (Ultra Nate album)|Stranger Than Fiction]]'', which was released in 2001, featured the production work of artists such as [[Attica Blues (band)|Attica Blues]], [[4 Hero]], and Mood II Swing. Four singles were released: \"Desire\", \"Get It Up (The Feeling)\", \"Twisted\", and \"I Don't Understand It\".\n\nNat\u00e9 contributed the song \"Wonderful Place\" to the AIDS benefit compilation ''Keep Hope Alive: A Lifebeat Benefit Compilation''. Additionally, in 2004, she released the singles \"Feel Love\", \"Brass in Pocket\", \"Time of Our Lives\" (released as \"Ultra Devoted featuring Ultra Nat\u00e9 and Gerry DeVeaux\"), and a new version of \"Free\" that features twelve new mixes. In 2005, she collaborated with [[Alex Gaudino|Gaudino]] and released the single \"Bitter Sweet Melody\". Later in the same year she found herself again on the charts, when her featured vocals on the [[StoneBridge (DJ)|Stonebridge]] single \"[[Freak On]]\" became a successful dance hit. She also performed on the British show ''[[Hit Me, Baby, One More Time (TV series)|Hit Me Baby One More Time]]''.\n\nHaving become a mother for the first time in the fall of 2005, Nat\u00e9 released her fifth album ''[[Grime, Silk, & Thunder]]'' on her newly created imprint Blufire in partnership with [[Tommy Boy Records]]. The first single released was \"[[Love's the Only Drug]]\", which became available through the US [[iTunes Store]] August 8, 2006 and reached number two on the American [[Hot Dance Club Play]] and made the Top 30 on the [[Hot Dance Airplay]] chart. The second single \"[[Automatic (Pointer Sisters song)#Ultra Nat\u00e9 cover|Automatic]]\" (a cover version of the [[Pointer Sisters]] hit) reached number one on the US [[Hot Dance Club Play]] chart (the week ending April 28, 2007). It also received airplay in the Rhythmic/Dance format radio where it reached the Top 30 of most playlists in this radio format. Following Automatic, Ultra released \"[[Give It All You Got (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Give It All You Got]]\" which features Chris Willis in Dec 2007. The song hit No. 1 on the ''Billboard'' Dance Music/Club Play charts the week ending February 23, 2008.\n\nIn mid-2009 it was announced that US singer [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]], previously of [[Destiny's Child]] has collaborated on a song with Ultra called \"I'm Waiting On You\", for use on both of their next studio albums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/a162286/michelle-williams-162286/|title=Michelle Williams|first=Nick|last=Levine|date=29 June 2009|website=Digital Spy}}</ref> In 2010 Ultra has released a Bob Sinclar remix of her hit \"Free\" on Strictly Rhythm. \"Give It 2 U\" in collaboration with Quentin Harris for his album \"Sacrifice\". She also released \"Destination\" in collaboration with Tony Moran which peaked at No. 10 on the Billboard Dance Play chart. \"Destination\" was the second single off Tony's album, Mix Magic Music.\n\nIn 2010 she released an EP titled \"Things Happen At Night\" featuring Ultra's pop and soul melodies and vocals over percussive club beats done by Unruly productions. January 2011 is saw the release of Ultra's next single with Strictly Rhythm on her Deep Sugar label imprint called \"[[Turn It Up (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Turn It Up]]\" with a music video directed by Leo Herrera. \"Turn It Up\" was the first single to be released from her sixth studio album titled ''Hero Worship''.\n\nIn September 2011, she submitted the song, \"My Love\" to represent [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Switzerland]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012]], to be held in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]]. However, though close, the song failed to reach the final.<ref>[http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/17658 Eurovision Song Contest - Baku 2012 | News - Switzerland: American singer Ultra Nat\u00e9 on the race to Baku]. Esctoday.com. Retrieved on 2012-04-17.</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she held a residency spot at Cafe Ole at Space, Ibiza.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spaceibiza.com/en/news/item/1950-la-diva-del-house-ultra-nat%C3%A9-estrena-residencia-en-caf%C3%A9-ol%C3%A9-ibiza.html|title=House Music Diva Ultra Nat\u00e9 Starts Her Residence on Caf\u00e9 Ol\u00e9 Ibiza|last=|first=|date=July 22, 2013|website=Space Ibiza|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> Her spirited presence has graced the stages of New York's massive Summer Stage in Central Park, Nile Rodgers acclaimed FOLD Festival sharing the stage with the likes of CHIC, Duran Duran, Pharrell and Beck to Lincoln Center's annual Midnight Summer Swing and numerous Pride events around the world.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nUltra's 2017 album collaboration, ''Ultra Nat\u00e9 & Quentin Harris as Black Stereo Faith,'' reached the iTunes Top 10 upon release.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tantum|first=Bruce|url=https://5mag.net/features/black-stereo-faith/|title=Quentin Harris and Ultra Nate are Black Stereo Faith|date=September 5, 2017|work=5 Magazine|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Year !! Awards !! Work !! Category !! Result !! Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1998\n| rowspan=5|[[International Dance Music Awards]]\n| Herself\n| Best Dance Solo Artist\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=3|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418115208/http://wintermusicconference.com/idmaballot/nominees/archived/index.php?year=1998|title=Winter Music Conference 2015 - WMC 2015|date=April 18, 2015|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n